{
  "answer": "**Kātyāyana Smṛti** defines *śulka* (bride-price) in Chapter 75: \"Whatever value is received for household utensils, vehicles, milch animals, ornaments, and servants, that is declared to be the bride-price (*śulka*). // K_898 //\"[^1]\n\nThe same work caps gifts of a woman's separate property (*strīdhana*) by relatives in Chapter 76: \"*Strīdhana* should be given to a woman by her father, mother, husband, brother, and kinsmen, according to their ability, up to two thousand, but not immovable property. // K_902 //\"[^2]\n\n[^1]: Kātyāyana Smṛti, [Chapter 75](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/75/translation/#p-9e5207).\n[^2]: Kātyāyana Smṛti, [Chapter 76](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/76/translation/#p-f86392).",
